                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><MudChip T="string" Size="@MudBlazor.Size.Small">Ctrl + Z</MudChip></td>
                            <td>Undo last action</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </MudSimpleTable>
            </MudPaper>
        </MudItem>

        <!-- Core Concepts -->
        <MudItem xs="12">
            <MudPaper Class="pa-4 mb-4" Elevation="2">
                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6" Class="mb-3">
                    <MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Filled.School" Class="mr-2" />
                    Core Concepts
                </MudText>
                <MudGrid>
                    <MudItem xs="12" md="4">
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.subtitle1" Class="mb-2" Style="font-weight: 600">DAD Security Model</MudText>
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Color="Color.Secondary">
                            <strong>Disclosure</strong> — field-level control over who sees what data.
                            <strong>Alteration</strong> — cryptographically signed, immutable transaction history.
                            <strong>Destruction</strong> — P2P replication ensures no single point of failure.
                        </MudText>
                    </MudItem>
                    <MudItem xs="12" md="4">
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.subtitle1" Class="mb-2" Style="font-weight: 600">Blueprints & Actions</MudText>
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Color="Color.Secondary">
                            Blueprints define multi-party workflows. Each action has a sender, data schema, routes (what happens next), and disclosures (who sees what). The engine validates, calculates, routes, and discloses automatically.
                        </MudText>
                    </MudItem>
                    <MudItem xs="12" md="4">
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.subtitle1" Class="mb-2" Style="font-weight: 600">Registers & Dockets</MudText>
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Color="Color.Secondary">
                            A register is a ledger that stores transactions. Transactions are SHA-256 chain-linked and sealed into dockets (blocks) after validator consensus. Each register has its own governance roster.
                        </MudText>
                    </MudItem>
                </MudGrid>
            </MudPaper>
        </MudItem>

        <!-- FAQ -->
        <MudItem xs="12">
            <MudPaper Class="pa-4 mb-4" Elevation="2">
                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6" Class="mb-3">
                    <MudIcon Icon="@Icons.Material.Filled.QuestionAnswer" Class="mr-2" />
                    Frequently Asked Questions
                </MudText>
                <MudExpansionPanels>
                    <MudExpansionPanel Text="What is Sorcha?">
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Color="Color.Secondary">
                            Sorcha is a distributed ledger platform for orchestrating secure, multi-party workflows. It implements the DAD security model (Disclosure, Alteration, Destruction) so that multiple organizations can collaborate on shared processes while each party controls exactly what data they reveal.
                        </MudText>
                    </MudExpansionPanel>
                    <MudExpansionPanel Text="What is a Blueprint?">
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Color="Color.Secondary">
                            A blueprint is a workflow definition that specifies the sequence of actions, participants, data schemas, routes, and disclosure rules. Think of it as a contract that defines how a multi-party process flows — who does what, what data is required, and who can see each piece of information. You can build blueprints visually with the Designer or define them as JSON/YAML.
                        </MudText>
                    </MudExpansionPanel>
                    <MudExpansionPanel Text="How does selective disclosure work?">
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Color="Color.Secondary">
                            Each action in a blueprint can define disclosure rules using JSON Pointers (RFC 6901). When a participant submits data, the engine evaluates the disclosure rules and reveals only the specified fields to each recipient. For example, a buyer might see product name and quantity, while a supplier sees product name and unit price — neither sees the other's sensitive fields.
                        </MudText>
                    </MudExpansionPanel>
                    <MudExpansionPanel Text="What are Verifiable Credentials?">
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Color="Color.Secondary">
                            Sorcha implements SD-JWT Verifiable Credentials aligned with eIDAS 2.0. These are cryptographically signed attestations that can be selectively disclosed — for example, proving you hold a valid certification without revealing its expiry date or issuing authority. Workflows can require credential presentation before allowing actions (credential gating), and can issue credentials as proof of workflow completion.
                        </MudText>
                    </MudExpansionPanel>
                    <MudExpansionPanel Text="What cryptographic algorithms are supported?">
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Color="Color.Secondary">
                            Sorcha supports three signing algorithms: <strong>ED25519</strong> (fastest, recommended), <strong>NIST P-256</strong> (FIPS-compliant, wide enterprise adoption), and <strong>RSA-4096</strong> (legacy compatibility). Payload encryption uses <strong>AES-256-GCM</strong>, and transaction hashing uses <strong>SHA-256</strong>. All wallets are BIP32/BIP39/BIP44 hierarchical deterministic wallets.
                        </MudText>
                    </MudExpansionPanel>
                    <MudExpansionPanel Text="How does register governance work?">
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Color="Color.Secondary">
                            Each register has a governance roster with three roles: <strong>Owner</strong> (full control), <strong>Admin</strong> (can vote), and <strong>Member</strong> (can submit transactions). Adding or removing admins requires quorum voting — a majority of existing voting members must approve. All governance operations are recorded as immutable Control Transactions on the ledger itself, creating a complete audit trail.
                        </MudText>
                    </MudExpansionPanel>
                    <MudExpansionPanel Text="What happens when a node goes offline?">
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Color="Color.Secondary">
                            The P2P network ensures resilience through automatic replication. When a node comes back online, it syncs missed transactions from its peers. Pending transactions are queued locally and automatically flushed when connectivity is restored. The gossip protocol reaches 90% of the network in under 60 seconds for new updates.
                        </MudText>
                    </MudExpansionPanel>
                    <MudExpansionPanel Text="What standards does Sorcha comply with?">
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Color="Color.Secondary">
                            Sorcha implements: <strong>eIDAS 2.0</strong> (electronic attestations), <strong>SD-JWT VC</strong> (selective disclosure credentials), <strong>W3C DID</strong> (decentralized identifiers), <strong>BIP32/39/44</strong> (HD wallets), <strong>FIPS 186-4 &amp; 180-4</strong> (government-grade crypto), <strong>JSON Schema Draft 2020-12</strong> (data validation), and <strong>RFC 6901</strong> (JSON Pointer for field addressing).
                        </MudText>
                    </MudExpansionPanel>
                </MudExpansionPanels>
            </MudPaper>
        </MudItem>

